  "prompt": "How many ways can a 4-digit number be formed using the digits 3, 4, 4, 4, 5, 6, 6 and 7?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, let's count the total digits we have:\n   \u2022 1 three\n   \u2022 1 five\n   \u2022 1 seven\n   \u2022 3 fours\n   \u2022 2 sixes\n\n2) We want to form a 4-digit number using these 7 digits\n\n3) This is a permutation problem with repeated digits\n\n4) If all digits were unique, the number of permutations would be 7!\n\n5) However, we have repeated digits:\n   \u2022 4 appears 3 times\n   \u2022 6 appears 2 times\n\n6) We need to divide 7! by the number of permutations of the repeated digits:\n   \u2022 3! for the repeated 4\n   \u2022 2! for the repeated 6\n\n7) The formula is:\n   7! \u00f7 (3! \u00d7 2!)\n\n8) Let's calculate:\n   7! = 7 \u00d7 6 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 4 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1 = 7 \u00d7 6 \u00d7 5 \u00d7 4 \u00d7 3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1 = 5,040\n   3! = 3 \u00d7 2 \u00d7 1 = 6\n   2! = 2 \u00d7 1 = 2\n\n9) 5,040 \u00f7 (6 \u00d7 2) = 5,040 \u00f7 12 = 420\n\nTherefore, there are 420 ways to form a 4-digit number using these digits.\n\nThe answer is 420.",
